the\nexternal actions. Mind may be withdrawn completely f=\r\nrom the body and\nabsorb fully in the mantra at some stage then.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; Fro=\r\nm the point of view, japam (sitting still and meditating on a\nmantra) is th=\r\ne ultimate sadhana.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; However, not everyone can reach god like that. =\r\nThere are so many\nvasanas (conditioning) in the mind that needs to be purge=\r\nd/purified\nslowly. Until that is done, japam may not help one reach god. Un=\r\ntil\nthen, taking the help of an external pure object (such as fire) that ha=\r\ns\na purifying effect on one&#39;s subtle consciousness can be helpful. It\n*prep=\r\nares* one for good japam.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; * * *\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; A lot of priests do homam a=\r\nnd then leave the fire and go away. In\nthe homam manuals, I have made it a =\r\npoint to insist that people do japam\nwith their favorite mantra at the end =\r\nof the homam, while sitting still\nwith closed eyes. The idea is that homam =\r\npurifies subtle consciousness\nand *prepares* one for reaching god, while it=\r\n is finally japam that\ntakes one to god. After every homam, one&#39;s internal =\r\npurity is at a\nmaximum (a local maximum, temporally speaking - sorry for th=\r\ne technical\njargon) and japam will be more fruitful than at other times.\n&gt; =\r\n&gt;\n&gt; &gt; * * *\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; Now onto other questions:\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; (1) It is unfruitful =\r\nin the sense that it does not take you closer\nto god. It is fruitful in the=\r\n sense that it stops you from going much\nfurther away from god. After all, =\r\nif you weren&#39;t engaged in that japam\nand you were doing some other activity=\r\n, probably your mind will wander\neven more.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; I suggest looking at di=\r\nsturbing thoughts in the middle of a japam as\na heckler interrupting your s=\r\npeech. Instead of arguing and fighting with\nthe heckler, simply take note o=\r\nf him, pause for a second and move on.\nInstead of panicking or worrying, si=\r\nmply take note of your thoughts,\npause for a second and move on.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; (2=\r\n) Mantra means that which protects (tra) the mind (mana). Various\nvasanas (=\r\nconditioning) are pulling the mind in different directions to\nreact to vari=\r\nous situations in various ways and that activity tires out\nthe mind. You pr=\r\notect it by anchoring it in a mantra and teaching it to\novercome the pulls =\r\nof vasana.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; The proof of whether a mantra or japam or homam is worki=\r\nng for you\nor not is whether there is a slow internal transformation in you=\r\n or not,\nwhether your internal reaction to various external things is chang=\r\ning\nfor the better or not.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; (3) Difficult. This is where a good guru=\r\n is helpful.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; Actually, in this age, technical perfection is almost =\r\nruled out. I\nsuggest doing whatever one does with a sense of surrender and =\r\nhumility.\nIf there is something partly correct that somebody is doing, it w=\r\nill\nslowly increase with time and Nature will remove imperfections with\ntim=\r\ne.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; (4) I can write Obama&#39;s name and Gordon&#39;s name on sheets of pape=\r\nr\nnext to me and pretend that they came there and sat there. Will they\nreal=\r\nly do it? On the other hand, if I am a world leader holding a\nsummit, proba=\r\nbly I can make them actually come and sit there.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; Nyasa means placem=\r\nent. When you do nyasa, you place various\nvibrations (sound patterns) or en=\r\nergies (deities) in various body parts.\nFor most of us with distracted mind=\r\ns, it is merely a formality and means\nnothing. Only a sadhaka with a pure, =\r\npointed and focused mind can\nactually place various vibrations and energies=\r\n in various body parts.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; I always suggest to people to do nyasa as t=\r\naught by elders (so that\nthe knowledge lives and is passed on), but not wor=\r\nry too much about it.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; As I said, we are in the midst of deepening K=\r\nali and the level of\nsadhakas is not as high as in the old days. Technical =\r\nperfection will\nbecome rarer and rarer. It is better to focus on surrender =\r\nand humility.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; Best regards,\n&gt; &gt; Narasimha\n&gt; &gt; ------------ --------=\r\n- --------- --------- --------- --------- -\n&gt; &gt; Free Jyotish Software, Free=\r\n Jyotish Lessons, Jyotish Writings,\n&gt; &gt; &quot;Do It Yourself&quot; ritual manuals for=\r\n short Homam and Pitri Tarpana:\n&gt; &gt; http://www.VedicAst rologer.org\n&gt; &gt; Fil=\r\nms that make a difference: http://SaraswatiFil ms.org\n&gt; &gt; Spirituality: htt=\r\np://groups. yahoo.com/ group/vedic- wisdom\n&gt; &gt; Jyotish writings: http://gro=\r\nups. yahoo.com/ group/JyotishWri tings\n&gt; &gt; ------------ --------- ---------=\r\n --------- --------- --------- -\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; ---- Veneet Kumar kveneet@yahoo. c=\r\nom&gt; wrote:\n&gt; &gt; &gt; In the Bhagvata Gita, Krishna says that I am &quot;Japa&quot; amongs=\r\nt all\nYajnas. This statement establishes the supremacy of Japa over all oth=\r\ner\nkinds of rituals. I have the following queries regarding Japa.\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;=\r\n &gt; 1) Many a times while doing japa the mind wanders. The chanting\ndone at =\r\nthese instants are done without any &quot;bhavana&quot; or sense of\ndevotion in the m=\r\nind and are merely a physical chanting. Are such japas\nunfruitful?\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; =\r\n&gt; &gt; 2) Is there some way to validate that the japa shall actually\nbring cer=\r\ntain merits or nullify the targeted evils?\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; 3) How can an ordina=\r\nry person determine whether the japa he is\ndoing (or has done) is being don=\r\ne in a proper manner? For example if\nthere was some error in pronunciation =\r\nor some nyasa was not performed\ncorrectly which invalidated the japa - can =\r\nit be de