ith &quot;Om&quot;, becau=\r\nse Krishna said I am &quot;Om&quot; among mantras? Of course, not.&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&=\r\ngt; &gt; Same thing holds to japam vs other sadhanas such as homam.&lt;br&gt;&gt;=\r\n &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; Just as one may need ropes and other gear to climb moun=\r\nt everest, one may need to employ mantras other than &quot;Om&quot; and practices oth=\r\ner than &quot;japam&quot; to overcome one&#39;s short-comings and reach the summit of the=\r\n absolute, represented by Om (and all other things mentioned by Krishna).&lt;b=\r\nr&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; * * *&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; When you do an e=\r\nxternal sacrifical ritual such as homam, your body is engaging in actions. =\r\nSo your mind has to be attached to the body and use it in a particular way.=\r\n Can one reach samadhi while doing homam? Unlikely. One is more likely to r=\r\neach samadhi when one stops the external actions. Mind may be withdrawn com=\r\npletely from the body and absorb fully in the mantra at some stage then.&lt;br=\r\n&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; From the point of view, japam (sitting still and m=\r\neditating on a mantra) is the ultimate sadhana.&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; =\r\nHowever, not everyone can reach god like that. There are so many vasanas (c=\r\nonditioning) in the mind that needs to be purged/purified slowly. Until tha=\r\nt is done, japam may not help one reach god. Until then, taking the help of=\r\n an external pure object (such as fire) that has a purifying effect on one&#39;=\r\ns subtle consciousness can be helpful. It *prepares* one for good japam.&lt;br=\r\n&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; * * *&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; A lot of priests =\r\ndo homam and then leave the fire and go away. In the homam manuals, I have =\r\nmade it a point to insist that people do japam with their favorite mantra a=\r\nt the end of the homam, while sitting still with closed eyes. The idea is t=\r\nhat homam purifies subtle consciousness and *prepares* one for reaching god=\r\n, while it is finally japam that takes one to god. After every homam, one&#39;s=\r\n internal purity is at a maximum (a local maximum, temporally speaking - so=\r\nrry for the technical jargon) and japam will be more fruitful than at other=\r\n times.&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; * * *&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; Now ont=\r\no other questions:&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; (1) It is unfruitful in the s=\r\nense that it does not take you closer to god. It is fruitful in the sense t=\r\nhat it stops you from going much further away from god. After all, if you w=\r\neren&#39;t engaged in that japam and you were doing some other activity, probab=\r\nly your mind will wander even more.&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; I suggest lo=\r\noking at disturbing thoughts in the middle of a japam as a heckler interrup=\r\nting your speech. Instead of arguing and fighting with the heckler, simply =\r\ntake note of him, pause for a second and move on. Instead of panicking or w=\r\norrying, simply take note of your thoughts, pause for a second and move on.=\r\n&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; (2) Mantra means that which protects (tra) the =\r\nmind (mana). Various vasanas (conditioning) are pulling the mind in differe=\r\nnt directions to react to various situations in various ways and that activ=\r\nity tires out the mind. You protect it by anchoring it in a mantra and teac=\r\nhing it to overcome the pulls of vasana.&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; The pro=\r\nof of whether a mantra or japam or homam is working for you or not is wheth=\r\ner there is a slow internal transformation in you or not, whether your inte=\r\nrnal reaction to various external things is changing for the better or not.=\r\n&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; (3) Difficult. This is where a good guru is hel=\r\npful.&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; Actually, in this age, technical perfectio=\r\nn is almost ruled out. I suggest doing whatever one does with a sense of su=\r\nrrender and humility. If there is something partly correct that somebody is=\r\n doing, it will slowly increase with time and Nature will remove imperfecti=\r\nons with time.&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; (4) I can write Obama&#39;s name and =\r\nGordon&#39;s name on sheets of paper next to me and pretend that they came ther=\r\ne and sat there. Will they really do it? On the other hand, if I am a world=\r\n leader holding a summit, probably I can make them actually come and sit th=\r\nere.&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; Nyasa means placement. When you do nyasa, y=\r\nou place various vibrations (sound patterns) or energies (deities) in vario=\r\nus body parts. For most of us with distracted minds, it is merely a formali=\r\nty and means nothing. Only a sadhaka with a pure, pointed and focused mind =\r\ncan actually place various vibrations and energies in various body parts.&lt;b=\r\nr&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; I always suggest to people to do nyasa as taught =\r\nby elders (so that the knowledge lives and is passed on), but not worry too=\r\n much about it.&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; As I said, we are in the midst o=\r\nf deepening Kali and the level of sadhakas is not as high as in the old day=\r\ns. Technical perfection will become rarer and rarer. It is better to focus =\r\non surrender and humility.&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; Best regards,&lt;br&gt;&gt;=\r\n &gt; Narasimha&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; ------------ --------- --------- --------- ---=\r\n------ --------- -&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; Free Jyotish Software, Free Jyotish Lessons=\r\n, Jyotish Writings,&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; &quot;Do It Yourself&quot; ritual manuals for short =\r\nHomam and Pitri Tarpana:&lt;br&gt;&gt; &gt; http://www.VedicAst rologer.org&lt;br&gt;&g=\r\nt; &gt; Films that make a difference: http://SaraswatiFil ms.org&lt;br&gt;&gt; &g=\r\nt; Spiritual